<subSubSection id="C33A3DDCFFB0A924FF03AA4DFCF4FF3B" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="762" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FF03AA4DFD01F940" blockId="38.[144,756,1644,1666]" box="[144,756,1644,1666]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FF03AA4DFED4F943" box="[144,289,1645,1666]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<typeStatus id="549BD0F5FFB0A925FF03AA4DFF31F943" box="[144,196,1645,1666]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Type</typeStatus>
species:
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FEB8AA4CFD01F940" authority="Warren, 1899" authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1899" box="[299,756,1644,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Comostolodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subhyalina">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FEB8AA4CFDBBF940" box="[299,590,1644,1665]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Comostolodes subhyalina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB113A6FFB0A925FDC4AA4CFD01F940" author="Warren W" box="[599,756,1644,1665]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" pagination="1 - 66" refId="ref36320" refString="Warren W. 1899. New species and genera of the families Drepanulidae, Thyrididae, Uraniidae Epiplemidae, and Geometridae from the Old-World Regions. Novitates Zoologicae 6: 1 - 66." type="journal article" year="1899">Warren, 1899</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FF03AA86FEE4F97A" blockId="38.[144,273,1702,1723]" box="[144,273,1702,1723]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FF03AA86FEE4F97A" box="[144,273,1702,1723]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FF03AAFEFEF1F8AE" blockId="38.[144,759,1758,1903]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FF03AAFEFF14F932" box="[144,225,1758,1779]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Adults:</emphasis>
Antenna in male basally bipectinate, terminally filiform, filiform in female. Frons moderately protruding. Labial palpus elongate in female. Hind tibia in male dilated, with hair-pencil and terminal extension.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCACACE6FBD1FD66" blockId="38.[806,1422,198,1046]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
Wing shape and pattern. Wings green. Forewing a narrow white band along costal area, bordered externally and internally purple-red, extending inwards at one-third and two-thirds; marginal area similarly bordered, appearing as linked bead-like white patches, larger on tornal angle and sometimes on M 
<subScript id="17A46C12FFB0A925FA9CAD49FAE2FEB4" attach="left" box="[1295,1303,361,373]" fontSize="5" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">3</subScript>
, the other patches being approximately of equal size; another three white spots ringed with purplish red present respectively on the middle of M 
<subScript id="17A46C12FFB0A925FB35ADE5FB5BFE10" attach="right" box="[1190,1198,453,465]" fontSize="5" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">3</subScript>
, the base of CuA 
<subScript id="17A46C12FFB0A925FA16ADE5FA78FE10" attach="left" box="[1413,1421,453,465]" fontSize="5" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">2</subScript>
(quite small) and the middle of the inner margin. Hindwing with outer margin area similar to forewing, and the middle of the inner margin with a long and narrow purplish-red streak. Brown discal spots on both wings small. Underside much paler, dull whitish green; forewing with costal area brown; streaks on upperside discernible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCACAE8FFB84FCC3" blockId="38.[806,1422,198,1046]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">The eighth segment is modified, both the tergite and sternite being concave at middle, with a pair of sclerotized lateral processes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCACAF2BFAADFC5D" blockId="38.[806,1422,198,1046]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
Male genitalia. Uncus vestigial. Socii developed, tapering. Gnathos indistinct and ring-like. Valva short, simple. Saccus developed, tongue-like. Aedeagus broader than that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FBE6AF47FB00FCBD" box="[1141,1269,871,892]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Comibaena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FBE6AF47FB00FCBD" box="[1141,1269,871,892]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Comibaena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sclerotized, coecum penis more slender than aedeagus body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCACAF84FC2EFBD7" blockId="38.[806,1422,198,1046]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Female genitalia. Sterigma simply to complexly modified. Ductus bursae very slender or quite short. Corpus bursae large or small, very weak. Signum absent.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCB5A865FBC0FB35" blockId="38.[806,1421,1093,1268]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FCB5A865FC68FB9B" box="[806,925,1093,1114]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The wing pattern of this genus is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FC60A843FB4DFBB9" authorityName="WARREN" authorityYear="1896" box="[1011,1208,1123,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Chlorochromodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FC60A843FB4DFBB9" box="[1011,1208,1123,1144]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Chlorochromodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FB60A844FA73FBB8" authorityName="TURNER" authorityYear="1910" box="[1267,1414,1124,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Argyrocosma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FB60A844FA73FBB8" box="[1267,1414,1124,1145]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Argyrocosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FB19A8A3FAEAFB59" authorityName="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue" authorityYear="2012" box="[1162,1311,1155,1176]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Linguisaccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FB19A8A3FAEAFB59" box="[1162,1311,1155,1176]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Linguisaccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are quite different from those two genera in having a simple, tongue-like, not bifid saccus, and in the simple valva lacking any decoration.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCB5A903FAD2FAF8" blockId="38.[806,1319,1315,1337]" box="[806,1319,1315,1337]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FCB5A903FC4DFAF9" box="[806,952,1315,1336]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F3372EC7FFB0A925FC51A903FBFFFAF8" box="[962,1034,1315,1337]" name="China" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3372EC7FFB0A925FB8BA903FBA2FAF8" box="[1048,1111,1315,1337]" name="India" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3372EC7FFB0A925FBF6A903FB59FAF8" box="[1125,1196,1315,1337]" name="Nepal" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3372EC7FFB0A925FB29A903FAD6FAF8" box="[1210,1315,1315,1337]" name="Pakistan" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCB5A948FC82FA7B" blockId="38.[806,1421,1384,1466]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FCB5A948FC51FABC" box="[806,932,1384,1405]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Etymology:</emphasis>
The generic name, which is masculine, derives from the Latin words meaning tongue and saccus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A925FCB5A9CAFB48F99A" blockId="38.[806,1421,1514,1903]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FCB5A9CAFC67FA3E" box="[806,914,1514,1535]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB113A6FFB0A925FC0AA9CAFB93F9C1" author="Han H-X &amp; Xue D-Y" box="[921,1126,1514,1536]" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" refId="ref33609" refString="Han H-X, Xue D-Y. 2011. Fauna sinica (Insecta vol. 54, Lepidoptera, Geometridae, Geometrinae). Beijing: Science Press [in Chinese with English abstract]." type="book" year="2011">Han &amp; Xue (2011)</bibRefCitation>
reported that the distinct characters of the species known then as 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FA9EAA28FC50F9FD" authorityName=": Prout" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Comibaena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subhyalina">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FA9EAA28FC50F9FD" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Comibaena subhyalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might justify the erection of a new genus. We now formalize this proposition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F6E57FFB0A924FCACAA44FCF4FF3B" blockId="38.[806,1421,1514,1903]" lastBlockId="39.[164,779,198,250]" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="762" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
As explained in the Introduction, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FB6BAA45FA78F9BB" authorityName="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue" authorityYear="2012" box="[1272,1421,1637,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Linguisaccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FB6BAA45FA78F9BB" box="[1272,1421,1637,1658]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Linguisaccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a differently shaped saccus in the male genitalia from other members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FBEFAA81FAE5F976" authorityName="Inoue" authorityYear="1961" box="[1148,1296,1697,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Comibaenini">Comibaenini</taxonomicName>
, and thus lacks the principal synapomorphy of the tribe. However, its wing pattern is almost identical to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FCD1AADDFBF2F8D3" authorityName="WARREN" authorityYear="1896" box="[834,1031,1789,1810]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Chlorochromodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FCD1AADDFBF2F8D3" box="[834,1031,1789,1810]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Chlorochromodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FBD2AADDFB21F8D3" authorityName="TURNER" authorityYear="1910" box="[1089,1236,1789,1810]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Argyrocosma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FBD2AADDFB21F8D3" box="[1089,1236,1789,1810]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Argyrocosma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it shares a simple valva with 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FB8AAB3CFB8FF8F0" authorityName="BOISDUVAL" authorityYear="1840" box="[1049,1146,1820,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Thetidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FB8AAB3CFB8FF8F0" box="[1049,1146,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Thetidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FCB5AB1AFC53F88E" box="[806,934,1850,1871]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Comibaena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FCB5AB1AFC53F88E" box="[806,934,1850,1871]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">Comibaena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B954B245FFB0A925FC70AB1AFB61F88E" box="[995,1172,1850,1871]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="761">
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FC70AB1AFB65F88E" authorityName="HOLLOWAY" authorityYear="1996" box="[995,1168,1850,1871]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Protuliocnemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Protuliocnemis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
It does not fit in any other tribe of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB0A925FC60AB79FB7FF8AE" authorityName=", Hausmann" authorityYear="1996" box="[1011,1162,1881,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="772" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Geometrinae">Geometrinae</taxonomicName>
. Although the position is not entirely satisfactory, we consider that for the moment it is best retained within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2015D4FFB1A924FDFBACC4FD08FF3B" authorityName="Inoue" authorityYear="1961" box="[616,765,228,250]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="762" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Comibaenini">Comibaenini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
